–Female":"1000–Deceased","0996":"0996","1038":"1038","1027":"1027","1048":"1048","1035":"1035","1022":"1022","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","1108":"1108","Zouche":"Zouchen, Sancha, Xiaonan, Xiaogan, Hubei, China","England":"England","France":"France","Beaumais, Calvados, France":"Beaumais, Calvados, France","Harrington, Northamptonshire, England":"Harrington, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":13,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1356256,"age":16,"year":"1038","julianDay":2100182,"description":"Western Xia Dynasty. The Tanguts, relatives to the Tibetians, found the dynasty.","jurisdictionLevel":5},{"id":1705182,"age":44,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Beaumeis was born in 1022, in France, his father, Baron Richard de Belmeis, was 27 and his mother, Mabel de Beila, was 23. He had at least 2 sons with Mabel of Beaumais. He died in 1070, at the age of 48, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1022–1070":"1022–1070","1027–Female":"1027–Surnud","1048–1108":"1048–1108","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","0996–Male":"0996–Surnud","1000–Female":"1000–Surnud","0996":"0996","1038":"1038","1027":"1027","1048":"1048","1035":"1035","1022":"1022","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","1108":"1108","Zouche":"Zouchen, Sancha, Xiaonan, Xiaogan, Hubei, Hiina","England":"England","France":"Prantsusmaa","Beaumais, Calvados, France":"Beaumais, Calvados, Prantsusmaa","Harrington, Northamp